snippet.title: Paris 19th Arrondissement - 20 in 20 Day 19 - Basin de la Villette to Buttes-Chaumont Paris
snippet.description:
Paris' 19th arrondissement isn't necessarily the most touristed, but that doesn't mean you should skip it - especially Basin de la Vilette (a section of Canal Saint Martin) and Buttes Chaumont. Grab my guide to Paris here: http://bit.ly/ParisVloggersGuide for my recommendations on food, drinks, and coffee along the canal and around the 19th district of Paris.

Patrons in the Wanderer category and up can also get access to my Mapstr which gets updated in real time: http://patreon.com/jayswanson and then find me on the internet in all of the usual spots:

More swag here:
http://bit.ly/ShirtOfTheMonth (shirts and hat)
http://bit.ly/JaysGearList (my gear and books)
https://gum.co/camerafour (Disposable Camera Four digital scans)

Follow me here:
http://twitter.com/jayonaboat
http://instagram.com/jayswanson

Music by: Dyalla

The 19th arrondissement of Paris is best known for Basin de la Villette and Parc des Buttes-Chaumont - a fantastic park in the northeast of Paris built by Napoleon III. While I wouldn't recommend staying here on your first visit to Paris (you can read why in my guide) I would definitely recommend a visit if you've got time.

My name is Jay Swanson - I'm an American writer living in Paris on an artist visa and hoping to make the city of light my home base - at least for the foreseeable future. I write science-fiction and fantasy, vlog daily, and love pizza a little too much.

Links below to Amazon are affiliate links - meaning if you click through them and buy something, I'll get some pennies. Thanks! (The FTC wants me to tell you that up front)

FAQ:
How long have you lived in France? On and off for over two years.

What do you miss most about ho- NACHOS

You're always talking about living on some ship. WHAT SHIP? - I made a "Draw My Life" video that explains a lot here: https://youtu.be/-MrvL37jTKM

Where are you from originally? - Pullman, Washington - a small university/agricultural town near Idaho (and yes, the potatoes are amazing).

What do you film with? - I've made a lot of changes recently, but I try to keep my gear list up to date if you want to see what I use and buy some for yourself: http://bit.ly/JaysGearList

What do you edit with? - Adobe Premiere - it's pretty much all I've ever used since high school.

Aren't you ever freaked out by leaving your camera behind to film yourself? - Yep. But not too badly - I tend to be careful when I do.

Why are you living in #Paris? - Because I've always wanted to; I feel at home here: https://youtu.be/4Vivf6MqMxQ

Do you speak French? Oui. https://youtu.be/va1QjaHgij8

You talk a lot about the books you're working on, what are they about? - They're sci-fi (and fantasy) and I've got a decent pitch for you here: https://youtu.be/W2bKt4_Tp4E

Do you make money off YouTube? - Ha, no. I wish. It took me over 500 videos to make my first total $100 off adsense. I think it will slowly change, but VERY slowly.

I really enjoy your videos, how can I support you? - The easiest and best way to support me is through Patreon, where you can pitch in as little as $1/mo to help me make better videos: http://patreon.com/jayswanson

I don't trust this Patreon thing - can I just paypal you? - Here's my ko-fi if that's your thing (and coffee is your game): https://ko-fi.com/jayswanson

But I want to send you something tangible! - I do have a wishlist on Amazon, though it's a bit complicated with the international shipping situation. This is the US one: http://amzn.to/2ykS9Ux

And here's the French wishlist: http://bit.ly/JaysFrenchWishList

Thanks for watching!

comments.textDisplay: Jay, you nailed it!! Thank you from the bottom of my heart for the Métro Jaurès footage. Out of the blue, I started bawling; I didn’t realize how much it would impact me to see my other home. When you passed the fountain with the Invader, I lost it. That was one the first things I saw when I arrived in Paris for the first time. I have a great pic of my son at that fountain, too. You all probably walked right past my old apartment— rue Lally-Tollendal. I feel fortunate there was a stage in my life there where I went to the Buttes Chaumont every day. I was lucky/blessed enough to be able to do that. Truly, thank you. This was absolutely perfect of the 19th. 🙏🏼💗

comments.textDisplay: Jay, I ran into your blog the day after the Notre Dame fire.  I was looking for stories on the fire....well one thing led to another and I started becoming captivated by your 20 in 20 series...that led me into wanting to learn more about you.  Well done sir!  I am 54, perhaps older than many of your viewers?  However, I have lived in Europe twice (Vienna and Berlin) when I was younger and traveled through Paris both of those times and on my honeymoon.  Your blogs really have brought me back to another time in my life but also have left me wanting to move back to Europe.  I really like your mix of personal stories and exploring.  Keep it up!  You have me hooked.

comments.textDisplay: I wish I could of accessed my internet before you went to the 19th.(phone issues in Europe)  Around the i/s of Botzaris and Crimee, several different space invaders.  I loved staying in the 19th at an airbnb right next to Buttes Chaumont.  Your tips really helped, my goal was to not be that tourist.  No troubles on the  Metro or on escalators.  Did not dress like a tourist, so the scammers left me alone while they went after obvious tourists.  Only when my German friend visited me and was speaking English did we have the gold ring scam outside the D'Orsay.   Only thing I did not account for is how warm and humid it was in Paris the week of 14/4/19.  Everyone was wearing coats and I was not wearing one at all.  As a suggestion, I would tell anyone visiting Paris not to take the open bus tour unless you want to spend all day in traffic.  Do your homework on what you want to see and take the Metro.  Only 5 days in Paris then spent the last 2 weeks in the Perigord.  While Paris is wonderful, there is so much more to see in France.
